üîç Find Person

Quickly locate and highlight a person in the tree:

  1. Click Find Person button
  2. Type or select a person's name from the dropdown (searches all 229 people)
  3. Click Find

The tree will center on that person with a distinctive red and yellow border highlight. Click Clear to remove the highlight.

üîó Relationship Finder

Find the relationship between any two people:

  1. Click Find Relationship button
  2. Select first person from dropdown
  3. Select second person from dropdown
  4. Click Find

The tree will show only the relevant path between the two people with colored highlighting!

üë• Cousin Finder

Find all cousins of a specific person:

  1. Click Find Cousins button

  3. Choose cousin degree (1st, 2nd, 3rd)
  4. Click Find

Rozwad√≥w

(Roz-VAH-doof)

A Karp Family Ancestral Town

Note: This article is still under development. More sections and information will be added.

Geography

Poland in Eastern Europe
Rozwad√≥w and the San River Region

From the first partition of Poland in 1772 until its reconstitution as an independent country in 1918, Rozwad√≥w on the left bank of the San River served as the northernmost town in Galicia, positioned on the border between Galicia and "Congress Poland."

Here, at the broadest section of the San River, the water flows slowly, flooding the low-lying left bank in the late winter months. Consequently, the town was frequently surrounded by a belt of marshlands to the east and north. The soil was poor, and the melting of snows or sudden summer rains from upstream frequently caused the river to rise and inundate the fields, destroying the peasants' scanty harvests. In 1911, to protect the town against these ravages, the Austrians built dykes on the lower parts of the left shore and reinforced the river banks by planting willow trees along their edges. This practical measure became the foundation for the famous basket-weaving industry that sprang up in the region, with its center at the neighboring town of Rudnik.

Generally, however, the land remained barren and largely unploughed. To the south and southeast, adjacent to the swamplands and forests, extended dry alluvial sandbanks. The only point of access to the river was at the village of Plawo, from where rafts of timber cut in the adjoining forests were sent on their several-week journey down to the Free Port of Danzig.

By the end of the nineteenth century, Jewish landlords of the Tarnobrzeg (Tar-NO-bshek) district held title to about 17,000 acres of land out of a total territory of approximately 175,000 acres. Jewish merchants and entrepreneurs controlled 14 landed estates, 114 taverns, 12 corn-brandy distilleries, 3 beer breweries, 14 flour mills, and 3 sawmills. Around the manorial estates gathered tradesmen and merchants who formed the nucleus for the townships that began to be founded along the river in the eighteenth century.

The earliest chronicles in which Rozwad√≥w is mentioned date back to the 1730s.

History

The early origins of Rozwad√≥w are difficult to trace due to the scarcity of historical source materials. However, it appears certain that the town grew from the adjacent village of Charzewice (Har-zheh-VEET-seh), much as the town of Tarnobrzeg had its origins in the village of Dzikow (JEE-koof).

For many years, the land on which the town was built belonged to a family of nobles named Roiewski. In the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, the area between the Vistula and San rivers passed into the hands of the Princes Lubomirski and Tarnowski. The Lubomirskis built their palace in the village of Charzewice, at the site of a small, ancient parochial church.

A local chronicle relates that in 1727, the parish authorities petitioned Prince Georg Lubomirski "not to leave the House of God in ruins and that he may for his own sake deign to restore the building which was about to collapse." In this same context, Rozwad√≥w is mentioned as numbering thirty Jewish households.

In 1897, the head of the Capuchin monastery distributed a pamphlet calling upon parish members to raise funds for building a new church at Rozwad√≥w to replace the ancient church of Charzewice, which had been completely destroyed after the third partition of Poland in 1795. A cornerstone for the new church was indeed laid, though it seems Prince Georg Lubomirski was more interested in developing commerce and trade. The pamphlet even accused him of undermining the church and being in league with the Jews.

The Jews of Rozwad√≥w

The Rozwad√≥w suburb of Stalowa Wola (Stah-LO-vah VO-lah) was a thriving Jewish shtetl prior to World War II. It was closely associated with Tarnobrzeg and other nearby shtetls including Ulan√≥w, Mielec, and Dzikow. These communities, infused with vitality before 1939, were utterly destroyed during the Holocaust‚Äîdevastated further after having been affected by World War I only some twenty years earlier.

The Jews of Rozwad√≥w formed a religiously observant community, traditionally Orthodox in practice. The leading rabbi of Rozwad√≥w, like other rabbis of the region, followed Hasidic practice and was of the Horowitz family. Later, in New York, a Rozwadower Rebbe established a small synagogue on the Upper West Side, which continued for many decades after the war. Notably, the Rozwad√≥w synagogue was, until World War II, located on Attorney Street on the Lower East Side of Manhattan.

There are no sources indicating the existence of an organized Jewish community before the end of the eighteenth and the beginning of the nineteenth century. The community records of the Council of the Four Lands (which functioned until 1746) make no mention of Rozwad√≥w or of other Jewish communities within the area between Sandomir, Lezajsk, and Przeworsk‚Äîwhether in Tarnobrzeg, Nisko, or Rudnik. This absence does not necessarily indicate the absence of Jews in the area. On the contrary, there is good evidence of Jews living in the twenty rural communities of the parish of Charzewice.

"Take an example from the Jews of Rozwad√≥w. Although there are only 30 Jewish houses in the town, they nevertheless took one, embellished it and converted it into a synagogue. Not only the local Jews but Jews from the entire neighbourhood are coming there for their prayers."
‚Äî Bishop Szaniawski, 1727, during his visit to raise funds for the restoration of the church of Charzewice

This account shows that Rozwad√≥w had become the nucleus for the formation of a Jewish community and served as a center for all Jewish settlements in the parish of Charzewice. When Prince G. Lubomirski arrived in the first quarter of the eighteenth century, he saw to it that Rozwad√≥w, lying close to his palace, would become a center of trade and commerce for the surrounding rural communities within his domain. In this he was aided by the Jews living in the various villages and in Rozwad√≥w proper.

According to Balicki-Lipinski in their "History of Old Poland" (Vol. III, p. 482): "Rozwad√≥w with its Capuchin monastery and parish church belongs to the family of Prince Lubomirski. His forefather, G. Lubomirski, one of the commanders of the Royal regiments, tried to improve the lot of the townsmen‚Äîhis poor subjects‚Äîand in 1714 procured from King August III privileges to hold two market days a week, on Sundays and on Thursdays."

It may be assumed that these fairs attracted an increasing number of Jews, who were the primary craftsmen and merchants of the time. This development was, however, slowed by hostile laws enacted against the Jews during the second half of the eighteenth century, as well as by the pogroms and persecutions to which they were constantly subjected.
